 "span": {"begin": 435, "end": 446}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:25350"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "[3H]mevalonactone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997682571411133, "span": {"begin": 458, "end": 475}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992601275444031, "span": {"begin": 478, "end": 490}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003687"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DHEA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987568855285645, "span": {"begin": 495, "end": 499}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MA-10CYP17KD cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9630884528160095, "span": {"begin": 644, "end": 662}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MA", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6496507525444031, "span": {"begin": 644, "end": 646}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011284"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "pregnenolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995546936988831, "span": {"begin": 684, "end": 696}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986409544944763, "span": {"begin": 698, "end": 710}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003687"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DHEA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986679553985596, "span": {"begin": 715, "end": 719}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1586"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP17a1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9601955413818359, "span": {"begin": 779, "end": 786}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006907"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17-OH-pregnenolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994729161262512, "span": {"begin": 790, "end": 808}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003687"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DHEA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9928694367408752, "span": {"begin": 823, "end": 827}}], "text": "A major empirical evidence came from CYP17 knock down cell studies. In 2005, Liu Y., Yao ZX., and Papadopoulos V. showed that MA-10 CYP17 knock down cells synthesize much less pregnenolone and DHEA compared with MA-10 wild type cells. In this study, de novo endogenous cholesterol synthesis was blocked with the 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coenzyme A (HMG-CoA) reductase inhibitor lovastatin. After cells incubation with a radiolabeled cholesterol precursor ([3H]mevalonactone), progesterone and DHEA were fractionned using HPLC and identify using standards. After quantification by liquid scintillation spectrometry, results indicated that the MA-10CYP17KD cells synthesize much less pregnenolone, progesterone and DHEA. These results enable to highlight the important factor of CYP17a1 in 17-OH-pregnenolone conversion to DHEA.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:16:42 +0000 2026"}